{
  "doc_id": "53495",
  "text": "Diabetes-induced chronic inflammation underlies multiple secondary pathologies including the foot ulcer (rev. in 1), which can be modeled using the Lepr db/db mouse (2). In both humans and mice [CITATION_1] , diabetes impairs the orderly transition from an early, inflammatory phase of repair to a later, prohealing stage, preventing timely healing. Excessive numbers of myeloid cells are found in the wound [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , and they display a persistent proinflammatory, M1-like (classical) or M1/M2 (mixed) phenotype, instead of a clear transition to an M2-like (alternative) state [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
